# =============================================================================
# PAM SSH 2FA - Example PAM Configuration for /etc/pam.d/sshd
# =============================================================================
#
# This file shows what changes to make to /etc/pam.d/sshd to enable 2FA.
# DO NOT replace your entire sshd PAM config with this file!
# Instead, apply the specific change shown in OPTION 1 below to your
# existing config's "auth" section.
#
# VALIDATED FINDING (see MODERNIZATION_PLAN.md, "the documented PAM stack
# may not match the promised flow"): earlier versions of this example
# said to add the 2FA module AFTER "@include common-auth". That was
# tested empirically with pamtester against a real PAM stack and found
# to be wrong in a way that matters:
#
#   - common-auth's pam_unix.so prompts for and validates a Unix
#     password BEFORE the 2FA module ever runs, so the actual flow
#     becomes "SSH key + Unix password + push code", not the documented
#     "SSH key + push code".
#   - If that password is wrong, pam_unix's fallback
#     (auth requisite pam_deny.so) aborts the ENTIRE stack immediately --
#     the 2FA module never even executes.
#   - For a password-locked account (passwd -l, or any account
#     provisioned SSH-key-only, which is this module's primary target
#     audience), pam_unix ALWAYS fails, so login is completely
#     impossible. 2FA can never be reached at all.
#
# The fix: the 2FA module should REPLACE "@include common-auth" in the
# auth stack, not follow it. SSH key verification already happened at
# the OpenSSH layer before this PAM stack is ever invoked (this stack
# only runs for the keyboard-interactive step tagged ":pam" in
# AuthenticationMethods) -- there is nothing for pam_unix to usefully
# re-check here, and including it only adds a hidden, sometimes-fatal
# extra factor.
#
# =============================================================================

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# OPTION 1 (RECOMMENDED): Replace common-auth with the 2FA module
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# This requires: SSH key + 2FA code -- and works regardless of whether
# the account has a Unix password set at all.
#
# In /etc/pam.d/sshd, REPLACE this line:
#
#   @include common-auth
#
# with:
#
#   auth required pam_python.so /etc/pam-ssh-2fa/pam_ssh_2fa.py
#
# Leave every other line in the file (account, session, password
# sections) exactly as it is -- those apply to all logins regardless of
# which auth method was used and are unrelated to this change.

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# OPTION 2: Also require a Unix password (three factors)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# If you specifically want SSH key + Unix password + push code, keep
# common-auth and add the module after it:
#
#   @include common-auth
#   auth required pam_python.so /etc/pam-ssh-2fa/pam_ssh_2fa.py
#
# WARNING: this makes login impossible for any account without a valid,
# unlocked Unix password (passwd -l, or a fresh SSH-key-only account
# never given one). Confirm every account that needs to log in actually
# has a working password before using this option, or they will be
# locked out with no indication that 2FA was ever reached.

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# OPTION 3: Make 2FA optional (soft fail)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# If 2FA fails (e.g., notification service down), allow login anyway.
# Less secure but prevents lockouts. Still replaces common-auth per
# OPTION 1 -- only the control flag changes.
#
#   auth optional pam_python.so /etc/pam-ssh-2fa/pam_ssh_2fa.py
#

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# OPTION 4: 2FA only for certain users (via PAM succeed_if)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# Only require 2FA for users in the "require2fa" group; everyone else
# authenticates with just their SSH key. Also replaces common-auth.
#
#   auth [success=1 default=ignore] pam_succeed_if.so user notingroup require2fa
#   auth required pam_python.so /etc/pam-ssh-2fa/pam_ssh_2fa.py
#
# Note: this module's own [bypass] users/networks config.ini setting
# (see README.md) is usually a simpler way to exempt specific
# users/networks, and doesn't require editing PAM at all.

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# COMPLETE EXAMPLE /etc/pam.d/sshd
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# This is what a Debian/Ubuntu sshd PAM config looks like with OPTION 1
# applied. The account/session/password sections below are exactly what
# ships in Debian's default /etc/pam.d/sshd -- verified against a real
# Debian 13 install while validating this file. Minor wording in these
# sections has drifted slightly release to release; leave YOUR existing
# file's account/session/password lines untouched and only change the
# auth line as shown.
#
# --- BEGIN EXAMPLE ---

# PAM configuration for the Secure Shell service

# === PAM SSH 2FA ===
# Push/OTP verification. Deliberately NOT preceded by @include
# common-auth -- see the header of this file for why.
auth required pam_python.so /etc/pam-ssh-2fa/pam_ssh_2fa.py
# === END PAM SSH 2FA ===

# Disallow non-root logins when /etc/nologin exists.
account    required     pam_nologin.so

# Uncomment and edit /etc/security/access.conf if you need to set complex
# access limits that are hard to express in sshd_config.
# account  required     pam_access.so

# Standard Un*x authorization.
@include common-account

# SELinux needs to be the first session rule.  This ensures that any
# lingering context has been cleared.  Without this it is possible that a
# module could execute code in the wrong domain.
session [success=ok ignore=ignore module_unknown=ignore default=bad]        pam_selinux.so close

# Set the loginuid process attribute.
session    required     pam_loginuid.so

# Create a new session keyring.
session    optional     pam_keyinit.so force revoke

# Standard Un*x session setup and teardown.
@include common-session

# Print the message of the day upon successful login.
# This includes a dynamically generated part from /run/motd.dynamic
# and a static (admin-editable) part from /etc/motd.
session    optional     pam_motd.so  motd=/run/motd.dynamic
session    optional     pam_motd.so noupdate

# Print the status of the user's mailbox upon successful login.
session    optional     pam_mail.so standard noenv # [1]

# Set up user limits from /etc/security/limits.conf.
session    required     pam_limits.so

# Read environment variables from /etc/environment and
# /etc/security/pam_env.conf.
session    required     pam_env.so # [1]
# In Debian 4.0 (etch), locale-related environment variables were moved to
# /etc/default/locale, so read that as well.
session    required     pam_env.so envfile=/etc/default/locale

# SELinux needs to intervene at login time to ensure that the process starts
# in the proper default security context.  Only sessions which are intended
# to run in the user's context should be run after this.
session [success=ok ignore=ignore module_unknown=ignore default=bad]        pam_selinux.so open

# Standard Un*x password updating.
@include common-password

# --- END EXAMPLE ---

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# VERIFYING THIS ACTUALLY WORKS
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# A PAM stack that parses fine (sshd -t passes) can still be semantically
# wrong -- there is no static check for "does this actually prompt for
# 2FA and nothing else." Before trusting this in production:
#
#   sudo apt install pamtester
#   sudo pamtester sshd <youruser> authenticate
#
# You should be prompted ONLY for the 2FA code/link -- never for a Unix
# password (unless you deliberately chose OPTION 2). If pamtester prompts
# for a password first, common-auth is still in the stack somewhere.
#
# Also test a password-locked account specifically if any of your users
# are SSH-key-only:
#   sudo passwd -l <youruser>   # if not already locked
#   sudo pamtester sshd <youruser> authenticate
# This should still work. If it fails immediately with no 2FA prompt at
# all, common-auth (or another module that requires a working password)
# is still ahead of the 2FA module in the stack.
